      "writtenOn": "2022-01-13T22:54:43Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I feel it just shifts the issue into RunConfig.  For example, a user will need to do\n\n  jail.run_config(\"/usr/bin/ls\", minijail::Config {\n    inheritable_fds: Keep(\u0026[libc::STDOUT_FILENO]),\n    args: \u0026[\"/usr/bin/ls\", \"-l\"],\n    env: Some(\u0026[\"LC_ALL\", \"C\"]),\n  })\n\nor\n\n  jail.run_config(\"/usr/bin/ls\", minijail::Config::new(\n    Keep(\u0026[libc::STDOUT_FILENO]),\n    \u0026[\"/usr/bin/ls\", \"-l\"],\n    Some(\u0026[\"LC_ALL\", \"C\"]));\n\nWe still need run_fd_config, and minijail::Config will full of lifetime specifiers internally.\n\nOn the other hand, if we had a config builder, the example would look like\n\n  jail.run_config(minijail::Config::new(\"/usr/bin/ls\")\n                    .keep_fd(libc::STDOUT_FILENO)\n                    .args(\u0026[\"/usr/bin/ls\", \"-l\"])\n                    .env(\"LC_ALL\", \"C\"));\n\nIt might not seem much, but minijail::Config will be extensible and can have all sorts of convenient methods like std::process::Command does.  Those familiar with std::process::Command also know how to use minijail::Config immediately.",
